Look, the game is fun and I'll continue playing it. But if you're an achievement hunter, just know that there's an achievement in the game called "The Pacifist" that you can only really get at the very beginning of the game. What is this achievement you may ask? Well, it's one where you literally wait for 2 hours in one session without killing anyone. This would be fine except for the fact that I wasted 4 hours of my life not knowing that you can't get it if you've already unlocked any other achievements. Which is stupid, because most players first instinct when getting this game is to kill someone, which is a achievement. All I'm saying is if you don't care for achievements, you should be fine, but if you're an achievement hunter make sure to be extra careful. Developer, if you're seeing this, I don't care if the achievement softlock thing is intentional or not, take it out of your game, it's garbage.

So, I've been playing this game for a little bit now, and i do have my pros and cons against People Playground.


For one, I really do think the game is not worth it's current price of $10. This seems more like a $5 game. I was expecting more, although it seems that it was a mistake.

The unique game gives you the freedom to do alot of things, when i was playing, i was making lasers, looking at other creations. although, thats about it. You either make your own stuff, or you see other's creations, the base game is pretty boring, and it gets very bland quickly. 

Although, when it comes to certain things on the game itself, like physics, visuals, ect. It's not all bad. A few things that i'd do to improve the game, would be to add new things, like more syringes, and their effects. I'd like to create a monster. Another thing that i'd like to see, it better AI. i wont lie, i like it now, although i feel like i'd love it more if they were more "Alive" than just standing there, perhaps have them walk around when they are idle, or have a function in game to have them act more alive. If i start to see changes, i will surely change my review, and my opinion entirely.

EDIT: So, after awhile i wanted to see if they have changed anything with the game itself. Turns out, they did! Although the game could use more work. At the current update, they have brought in new content, and the addition of mods, which makes the game more fun to play, and will keep you occupied for quite awhile. I still think at this stage, the price should be slightly lower, but besides from that, the game has hard working devs, that has passion for People Playground.

This game is basically a toy box for sadists. Sure, you CAN just play peacefully without harming a soul, building cool rocket cars and building houses. But that's not what you're going to do, is it? No, you're going to torture those poor pixel people. And you're probably going to enjoy it too.  You can spawn many different items, some for building, some for killing, and some for saving lives. What you do with these toys is all up to you and your imagination. Want to electrocute a dude whilst he's tied up and his friend is watching? Get it done. Do you want to grab a gun, slap a laser onto it and pretend you're some tacticool dude shooting people? Go for it. Do you want to get your little pixel people and make them have sexy times? Ehhhh.... there's probably a mod for it somewhere.

My original review for the game was a negative, simply because whilst I did enjoy the game, I couldn't play it for long or to its fullest potential, and I couldn't give a game a positive review if it's giving me so many crashes due to Unity not liking my GPU. That being said, even with those awful consistent crashes, I had racked up an extra 11 hours since my original review. That probably says quite a lot (both about me and the game).
Today a beta, 1.9b2, went live which enabled me to play the game using OpenGL as opposed to Direct3D11, and as far as I can tell so far, this has fixed my crashing problems. So huge thanks to the developer Zooi for taking the time to read my problems and finding a way to fix it, I can't think of many other games where the developer themselves will listen to your problem and slap it in a patch in less than a week or two.
ORIGINAL REVIEW BELOW

This is like mixing the concept behind a stressball with the concept of a sandbox type game like Garry's Mod, the game is still being worked on but i've made use of it almost daily whenever i've encountered a crappy situation and i need to let out some steam, it's also just really generally great if you're bored a lot.

I also have some suggestions for the developer, i'm not sure if others have made similar suggestions but here we go:

- Completely customizable ragdolls such as changing the size of both limbs (girth and lenght,) at once (basically a ragdoll customization menu), whether it's a male or female, the ability to change their color and their sprites, the ability to add MORE limbs so you could perhaps make monsters and demi-Gods or whatever your sick imagination would allow you to.

- The ability to change the color of blood and different effects, maybe even replace blood with different effects, for instance maybe change the blood to gasoline, which then in turn would catch fire if you shot rounds at it, which then could lead to a bleeding cyborg catching everything around it on fire, which reminds me..

- The ability to change different types of ammunition for different types of weapons, these could be hollow rounds, armor piercing rounds, incendiary rounds.. you get the drift.

- And the biggest suggestion yet, a type of basic/advanced editor that would allow you to make custom props and maps, i don't mean just using the game's already in-game mechanics (unless possible), i mean an editor on the side where you can make things from the ground up with sprites and some basic programming, this would lessen the workload on the developer and also make better use of the workshop feature.

These are again not REQUESTS but rather just some suggestions, i've been having a lot of fun with this little game, making all sorts of wacky and sadistic little creations and i look forward to every time there's a content update.

I can recommend this wholeheartedly if you're into sandbox games or if you like me were addicted to the abundance of ragdoll/stickfigure games that littered the browser gaming of the early-mid 2000's.


EDIT: I recently came up with a new suggestion, being able to take control over the ragdolls could change this game completely, being able to jump, crouch, walk, run, pick up items/weapons and maybe get in vehicles? in addition to some of my previous suggestions could easily make this into one of the best 2-D sandbox games currently on the market, that's just my thought anyway.

I'm not usually one to play Sandbox games considering how i can't usually think of things to do and i get bored. But when i found this game for only £1 and quite good reviews it seemed like a no-brainer to at least try it. 

People Playground is a Sandbox game where the main activity is well playing with people like a playground, however by "play" it means "murder and mutilate into a fine mist" so this means a good slew of swords, guns, axes and strange devices to be used to "play" with your happy little ragdoll before you can say "this is a bit inhumane isn't it" With a great Workshop community and new updates coming out for the game you can add lightsabers and weapons from S.T.A.L.K.E.R... for some reason. 

My main complaint with People Playground is that some groups of weapons don't really feel very unique between each other to justify trying them all out, for example if you've used a AK you've probably gotten the same experience as using a bunch of the other full auto rifle's or if you've used a desert eagle, you've probably experienced the same wonder as using any other regular pistol. 

So if you're very much into Sandbox games or want to make let off some steam by beating a bastard to death with a baseball bat or a metal rod or a sniper rifle etc, then be sure to check out People Playground! (also check out the Greenbrick workshop mod too its very nice) :)

This game is a must buy if you enjoy a sanbox game where you can just mess around.

There is Human and Android characters (Can make zombies), Both of these have their own properties like it would be harder to pierce or damage the Android.

Weapons. There are melee weapons which you can throw and stab people with, can slow down time to see it too. Guns to see the different powers behind each of their attacks. There are lots of weapons in the game

Different needles or drugs that do different things, one to make zombies, another to eat the flesh of a human and one to eat the bones. Some to heal the humans, there are 10+ different ones.

Different levels or maps with varying sizes, like a small room, large room, sloped map, Spartan kick hole. Guessing more maps will be added soon.

Different powers you can use, lighting, fire, drag the characters, force characters, so on.

Different objects to make the world stand out and set up your own scenarios, has wires to help make it fully customizable.

Bombs, pretty self explanatory but there are 5+ different bomb types like grenades, explosive barrels, nukes.

Now they have added mods, allowing various types of new weapons to be added like lightsabers and more guns and skyrim weapons, doom weapons. 

In conclusion the game is amazing, gets update frequently. Only problem I have is that I didn't find it sooner.

By far the absolute best sandbox game on the market, right next to Gmod. Nobody beats Gmod. If Gmod did not exist, this would be Gmod. Like stabbing? You can do that here. Like killing? You can do that too. Like playing with electricity, fire, poison, lasers, and other really dangerous things? You can do that here, and it's surprisingly realistic. The sound is eargasm, and this game is definitely superior to Mutilate A Doll 2. The content issue has been solved not only by the frequent updates, but the experimental mod support. THANK YOU DEVELOPER. Theres no point in even listing the pros and cons, as you just need to watch the trailer to see everything great about this game. The only thing that [i] could [/i] be a con is that the physics engine freaks out sometimes, but even then that only happens when you push the physics engine to its limits, and we all know that they ALWAYS freak out when pushed to their limits.


       This game will go very, very far with time. It's already going really far, and it's showing no signs of stopping anytime soon. I have a feeling even when the developer decides to just make this a legacy game or stop updating it, the community will keep it alive with mods and other things.

Great value and worth the money. This game is a great way to blow off some steam. While I love it in its current form, here are some things that I think should be added.

-More animations for humans (crawling, jumping, punching, etc.)
-More melee and ranged weapons to play around with.
-More models in general and textures for humans and androids.
-A way to script your own animations for human puppets, then they could have their own gunfights etc with each other.
-Better stabbing detection and gore in general.

There are also a couple of performance issues when a lot is happening on screen, but this game is a must buy if you're looking to relax and find new, twisted ways to kill 20 stickmen with a hand grenade.

This is the only game I've ever bought at full price, and I took a bit of a risk doing so. I was told it was an hour or two of fun at most, and that afterwards it was done, and you saw everything the game had to offer.

People Playground hit some sort of weird spot for me, a sandbox world that really feels both filled to the brim with content, but also like it's just barely scratched the surface of its potential. There's so many things to do; I've kept myself occupied in this game for nearly 50 hours and yet there are some mechanics I haven't even looked twice at. Speaking of which, this game has content for all types of people. Wanna mess with and test the limits of the ragdolls? There's tons of tools, weapons and body-altering juices that can do that. Wanna build crazy vehicles out of little more than metal rods and some cables? There's infinite possibilities with that. Wanna just be a maniac and blow stuff up? Theres plenty of tools for that, from hand grenades to atom bombs, and lightning strikes to black holes. Really, it'd be too tiresome to describe it all. so you're best off seeing for yourself.

Overall, I'm just a huge fan of this game. It sparked a love for creativity and experimentation I didn't really know I liked so much. A very fun time.

________________________________________________
[h1]𝓢𝓸, 𝔀𝓱𝓪𝓽 𝓲𝓼 𝓟𝓮𝓸𝓹𝓵𝓮 𝓟𝓵𝓪𝔂𝓰𝓻𝓸𝓾𝓷𝓭?[/h1]
People Playground is a sandbox game, similar to Mutilate-A-Doll 2, which was a popular flash game.
It is singleplayer only, however a multiplayer mode could be possible.
________________________________________________
[h1]𝓟𝓡𝓞𝓢:[/h1]
[list]
[*] Physics. They're very good and allow for cool catapults n' shit.
[*] The contraption building. You can build everything from simple presses to literal mecha robots in this game, and it's easy.
[*] The gore. Now, when you look at this game, you would think :[quote=You] Ay, this game is ugly and pixelated, it can't look good!!!11!! [/quote] But, the gore looks good enough for this kind of style, you can even see bone when shooting a person hard enough.
[*] The atmosphere. This game makes me feel like a real insane scientist doing weird experiments on clones, with the warehouse textures, the spooky ambient sounds, and all the secrets around, I feel like I'm an alien that is doing human experiments to take over the planet with ease.
[*] The workshop. The steam workshop for this game is full of people who probably spend more than an hour building mechs, vehicles, buildings, just for this game. It ain't Gmod, but you can build cool stuff here.
[*] The update schedule. Updates happen often, and they're packed full of new toys for contraption builders and serial killers alike.
[/list]
________________________________________________
[h1]𝓒𝓞𝓝𝓢:[/h1]
[list]
[*] The textures. Now, they're not [b] horrible [/b] per say, but for people who want 8k textures on all the games and run Nvidia RTX on everything they can, this is a pretty big downside.
[*] The physics also bug out sometimes, (i think, i haven't actually shot someone and looked at how they reacted) so people might jump when you shoot them instead of, y'know, acting like they got shot.
[*] The guns are hitscan, so you sadly can't view your shots in bullet time.
[/list]
________________________________________________
[h1]𝓣𝓲𝓹𝓼 𝓪𝓷𝓭 𝓽𝓻𝓲𝓬𝓴𝓼:[/h1]
Not much really, just that there are some cool easter eggs to fit the spooky ambience of it all.
[list]
[*] Don't [spoiler]watch the TV at 03:00 AM. (in real time)[/spoiler] Or do, if you aren't scared easily.
[/list]
________________________________________________
[h1]𝓞𝓿𝓮𝓻𝓪𝓵𝓵 𝓸𝓹𝓲𝓷𝓲𝓸𝓷:[/h1]
10/10. I fucking love this game. It's fun to play when you're not focused on it, just kinda throwing ragdolls around to pass time, and it's super fun to build contraptions when you [b] are [/b] focused on it. Now, the price might seem like a bit much, but this game gets updated often, and there'll be a hell of a lot more content in the future. Seriously, if you liked MAD2 back when flash was popular, you'll love this game.

This game is so gud. It is just so fun to mess around in it and I could do it for hours on end. I have a few minor suggestions for features that would be really nice to have in the game. Firstly, there should be more skins for humans and maybe an in game way to customize and save human textures to your liking similar to the object saving function. This would give people who make texture packs a lot more freedom and it would give more casual players who don’t even know what a mod is the option to design their own humans. Another suggestion is more syringes such as one that heals a person’s wounds once on contact and doesn’t infinitely heal that certain body part (I’m not sure if that is a glitch on my part or not.) Also another thing that would be really nice would be a way to rotate objects and humans in the opposite direction while active on the map. Idk maybe that would be hard to program or my ideas are just flat out stupid but yeah.

In the end though I think this game is awesome and I can’t get enough of it. Anybody reading this please get it. You will not regret it one bit.

People Playground:
Gameplay: This Game has the feeling of a classic 2D sandbox flash game, but bigger and with slightly less cruelty toward  everything the peoples of the game stand for, almost every thing can interact with something and you always seem to discover something new everytime you boot up the game. you can get almost anything you want out of people, machines etc. the people are also a LOT more fun to mess around with most charaters in these game are either godly bullet sponges and/or don't act realistic at all, You could take out a pistol shoot them in the knee then feed them a bowl of nail WITHOUT MILK and they'll be like "just another Monday." or worse you you touch them with a piece of paper and they spontaneously combust or freaking implode in front of your very eyes in this game though you shoot them and they're pain and bleed and bruise BUT they don't die they just got hurt, they act human and not like living ragdoll finally they get a bunch of updates meaning you get something new to tinker around with pretty consistently. overall the gameplays pretty good 
Requirements to play: a simple setup will give you pretty consistent gameplay as long as you don't spawn hunderds of things or create a bunch of explosions.
Price, is it worth it?: for the amount it cost you get a LOT (refer to Gameplay)
is it easy to learn (controls etc.) or if its hard to learn is it rewarding to learn?: There are a bunch controls and no tutorial so its hard to learn the game at first but once you get past the initial learning curve you get to tinker and discover tons of stuff.
FINAL SCORE: 8.5/10 very good for the price, not the best though (so far)

literally one of the best simulator games i've played in a really long time

i think we need a bit more stuff, but the game's got basically endless possibilities and you can do basically anything you could ever want to do to a ragdoll who responds to interactions (ex. stab wounds, gunshots, broken bones, water, blunt force, injections)

you can also grab some cars and bombs and just absolutely destroy any humans in your path if you want, and there's 20+ types of firearms if i remember correctly. you can also use the freezing mechanic to construct various things. you can literally build statues, buildings, skyscrapers, bridges, and tunnels. 

and did i forget to add that there's even more things like sentry guns and androids? yes, they exist in this game. you can literally make an android bodyslam an average human being into the floor and watch the poor guy explode under the pressure of the android.

my only suggestion to the dev is that we should get ballistic equipment and not have to makeshift it down the line. that'd be really nice.

overall, i 100% recommend this game. i've put 70 hours into it and i believe the game deserves every second of those 70 hours.

It got boring after one hour for me, mainly because you have to play this game like a kid who smashes his toys against each other and pretend that they are doing something. Dont get me wrong, its fun for like an hour, but then you realise how barebones this game is right now and how non-functional some things are. Not a lot of weapons, most of them work fine but grenades for example dont work like they supposed to. No Ragdoll AI to pep things up (at least i saw none cuz there is no detailed tutorial only controls). I found no way of making them shoot each other automaticaly like the turrets and i dont think that it even works. The Ragdolls respond good when they work but my god are they clunky 90% of the time. If you try to give them a weapon they wont even hold it straight or will simply fall over. The pause button doesnt work like it should do and just messes things up. When you want them to walk, they will often just fall over until you manually grab them up because they just cant go over obstacles.

Maybe ill rebuy it after 2-3 updates. But right now, it just feels like a demo.

Think of those old flash games you might of played as a younger child. You'd find them on those strange websites with hundred of games, websites of all the same or similar names, with all the same or similar games. 'Buddy games' you might of remembered them by, those games you'd see once but never remember the name of years down the line when you think back about it. They were all too much the same to one another anyway. This is like those games. Now it's modernized. It's fun. It is very fun. It is fun to spend hours creating bizarre contraptions, finding ways to interact with the maps, or simply just brutally torturing the funny little ragdoll people. And there is nothing wrong with having fun doing that. Eat your heart out with this game. Watch some gameplay on youtube, see if it clicks with you. You are spending money on this game, and these sort of titles don't have spoilers or anything like that, so watch the videos, analyze the UI, see what you can do in it, and you decide whether it's worth your money. It was worth mine. 

Now. I believe that this is a critical variable to consider before purchasing this game. I had only thought of it now, but it might matter to you. I haven't done the research myself, but I seriously suggest making sure whether or not updates are still being made for this game. If plans of such are not in place at the time of you reading this, then I highly suggest reconsidering unless you are totally sure that you are ok with what this game provides. There is nothing worse with getting sick of a game like this, updates keep things fresh, so make the call. 

Who knows... maybe watching this on youtube is enough for you instead of having to actually buy the game and setting up the scenes yourself. 

As always, make your call. Don't let anyone make it for you. Fun is fun... Not fun is torture. Boredom is a burden. A good game is suppose to alleviate that burden better than another game.

If you're looking for a sandbox game that lets you do pretty much everything with ragdolls, I suggest buying this game. Trust me, it's worth the full ten dollars. I'd probably spend my money on DLC's if there were any. Now if you're looking for a game that's not violent, just don't buy it. The game is full of blood and gore. So all y'all people who are not a fan of that stuff, just don't buy the game and then leave a review saying "oH I dIdN'T kNoW tHeRe WaS bLoOd. mY cHiLd iS nOw pErMaNeNtLy ScArReD!1!!!1 iM lEaViNg a bAd ReViEw!1!!!1!" Just don't. And anyways, who would dislike this game? The game is just beautifully made. I can tell the creators did a lot of hard work programming the AI to do certain things when something is triggered. Here is a list of pro's and con's about the game

PROS
-Beautiful Gameplay
-The AI/ Ragdolls respond to bullet wounds, bruises, stab wounds, and head injuries. This helps create realism.
-I can see where this game could be going. The updates are fairly large, and common like a few times a month. 
-I love how I can see what health/ or blood level certain body limbs are at. If you inspect a certain limb, you can see what the blood level, pain, consciousness, and adrenaline levels. and if you press 'C' you can view the health of the limbs.

CONS
-There are a few bugs
-Game is in 2D/ Which I'm totally fine with, it's just that when I shoot at the chest, the bullet sometimes hits the arms.

That's pretty much it for the review. You can play this game for hours. There are so many endless possibilities and ways to torture ragdolls.

Ok so this is my take on the game People's Playground.

1. If you want the TLDR; I would recommend this game.

2: There are a few points I would like to make. The first being the physics system. As it is a physics based game, you'd expect the physics system to be good. And you'd be right. In a few previous update there were small glitches in the physics system such as the human test subject's head would rapidly rock back and forth, resulting in the human launching themselves into the air. Also in previous update sometimes when stabbing the floor/frozen objects they would be teleported into the abyss to never be seen again.

3. Story. This game on its own has no story, as it's a sandbox game. One thing I've found to be entertaining is creating stories, using the many objects and now animations to create stories which over arch many different sittings to play this game. The system allowing you to save objects really helps with this too.

4. Machines. In this game, there are quite a few objects now to create murder machines with. Combing some of them creates something completely new to kill your miserable little human test subjects with. And especially with new updates coming fairly often now, you get a lot of content out of the game.

I know I don't have much hours on this game, but listen. This game is awesome. Never have I felt like stabbing innocent people more than when I am playing this game. The price is good for what you get, and the possibilities are not only endless but also fun and satisfying. If you need to get your anger out just open this game and stab humans or shoot them with the minigun lel. There's tons of cool items and stuff you can do to kill people in creative ways. If you look on the workshop the community makes some really cool stuff. Really enjoy and recommend.

[h1]I think it's time to make my very own review of this game.[/h1]

[b]So, i know most people love the gore stuff in this game, and i won't hide that i do too.[/b]

[u]But there is so much stuff to do in this[/u]...

This game is a mix between a disturbingly deep lore and a very dark setting. Some kind of "lab" created for the sole purpose of killing living beings. But it gets even darker once you find some... Disturbing things.
First, you can spawn a "human", but when you delete it, it says "person" removed. That sent some chills to my spine the first time i did it. But some things are even more disturbing. For exemple the existence of a very weird radio that hides a lot of secrets (I won't spoil you on this, you should too come down the rabbit hole :) ). But the most crazy thing about this is that the dev refuses the fact that this radio exists.

But overall this is a very well made game with crazy (and even somewhat disturbing in some ways) attention to detail; en even though i came across some minor bugs, this is a very good piece of programming (it's impressive knowing that only one person is behind this thing.)

[i]Psst, and if you're like me and aren't too sadistic, there is a lot of other ways to enjoy this game. For exemple i made tanks for the recently added workshop, and the realistic physics makes them very nice! This is so much more than a simple gore game.[/i]

The only flaws i can think of are the fact that the connecting wires are too big and blocks your line of sight. Having an option to hide them would be really nice.

[h1]9,5/10.[/h1]

Short and Simple, this game is a pretty interesting call back to the flash games of old. The basic functionality, the possibilities and combinations with what is given to you, that is what makes this game good. However, with that also lies some problems with it as well.

Replayability is shot pretty hard. There is only so much you can do in this game before nothing is left. I did mention earlier that there could be many possibilities to what you can do, but that can be quite limited. Sure, it's one of those "torture a dummy" flash games, so it's to be expected. However, with the asking price and the general public of the gaming community in recent times, the only people who'd probably purchase this are the ones who are of the days of those flash games and maybe a few curious people. That's my opinion on that, I could be wrong.

The variety of what you can do is somewhat plentiful. A lot of items and things to really cause chaos with the robot and humanoid figures you can spawn. Unfortunately, it could be much more, as some things work the same as others and the additional stages don't really add a whole lot to the overall experience. Perhaps Floor Hazards and other ways to manipulate the figures could be good things to add to the game.

Just to recap, here are the high and low points:

High Points:

1. Basic Functionality, making this a game to just sit down and play right away.

2. The possibilities of what you can do with the items you are given are quite plentiful. Maybe more if you put your mind to it.

3. The game is a call back to the Flash Games of old that older gamers are familiar with.

Low Points:

1. Replayability can be a problem, as what can you do in the game is limited due to similar functions to items, and the possibilities stated before is limited to what the player can think of.

2. The other stages provided in the game doesn't add much to the game other than another platform to cause whatever you want to cause with the figures.

3. The price, even though it is $9.99, can also be a problem. Given that this is basically the equivalent of a "torture a dummy" flash game with added functionality (or according to others, less content.), the amount of people that would pick up this game is quite small.

To conclude, this is a mixed bag to me. There is fun to be had with this game, and it *could* last for more than 2 hours unlike with me. Would I recommend this game? To me, it depends on the person and even then, it's up to what they think about if a glorified flash game is worth the $9.99 to get.

This is only just a review though, play the game if you wish and make your own opinion about it. That is the only way to know for sure how it's like. 

Note: I posted this as a positive review, as I am quite mixed on how I feel about this game. Even then, the low points I listed doesn't really warrant this to be a negative review.

A deceptively creepy and eerie yet incredibly fun game. There's lots of terrifying implications and creepy easter eggs to find on some of the maps, particularly on 'Abyss.' 

The game itself, if you are... technically inclined and like to build clever contraptions to murder all the people you can spawn, is incredibly fun. It's a little light on content, but there's enough here to entertain you for a good 3-4 hours intermittently when you're bored. Not to mention, it's got massive potential for updates, and has steam workshop integration for people to share their creations.
However, when you start the game, you're gonna want to turn the sound way down- the soundscape and sounds itself are incredibly high quality, but this also means that overlapping sounds can get into the realm of serious earrape. I recommend immediately lowering the volume to about half or lower as soon as you start the game, lest you break your eardrums when you get bored and slam a tank into the ground a few times at maximum velocity.

I definitely recommend it.

This is, hands-down, THE BEST ragdoll stress reliever game out there.

Pros:
>Good for passing time and relieving boredom.
>An insane amount of ways to maim and murder, the only limit is your imagination!
>Unique graphics that look good.
>Very active developer (As of right now, the most recent update was less than a week ago. Same thing for the update before that)
>Fun physics system.

Neutral:
>Incredibly graphic; people will writhe in pain, bodies will decompose, bruising and gore. Not for the faint of heart.
>$9.99 price tag. All in all I feel like it was worth it. Especially because it's just an indie dev who made this.

Cons:
>As of right now, the only AI implemented with the characters is that they react to pain. Zombies don't run after the humans to taste their flesh, they can't do much other than stand up when they're alive and fall over when they're dead.
>Controls a little difficult to get used to, no tutorial or prompts. You literally have to go into options, then click rebind keys to see what all your controls are.

Currently it is basically Mutilate-A-Doll 2, but not limited in performance by flash, instead it is Unity powered. You don't have the massive library of items, weapons and devices to interact with the ragdolls, instead you are given a simple arsenal of weapons and a lot of junk and mechanical and electrical components and expected to build your own torture devices and weapons, which is actually a solid design choice. I built a functining self-loading cannon that launches knives, even made a variant with a magazine well for a detachable magazine(however, due to the lack of spring constraints I have to use elaborate gravity operated cartridge feed and ejection systems that involve sliders, wheels and engines(that refuse to work like hinges when unpowered, by the way, making you have to design your machines without any form of hinges, there arent even servo motors)

I would normally consider that a disadvantage to just being given a massive library of premade items that arent janky or clanky, but I love creativity develops under tight constraints(pun not intended, but please fix, and make some basic digital logic stuff for automating parts too, I wanna build death robots and automatic slaughterhouses!)

So far, what I like about this game is the AI put into the ragdoll physics -how the ragdolls struggle, and move on their own.. not just boring and limp. I would like to see more of this aspect of the game come to life in the future, where they can even walk around, and crawl, and jump, and fight if you wanted them to. It'd be sweet to see them actually biting each other when infected with the zombie virus! I'd also love to see some sort of drawing mode, where you can easily create walls and different barriers, and reinvent the map sort of like the "Falling Sand" games. And maybe even an option to rewind, and redo.

The only problem I see with the game is the difficulty spawning things -having to go back and forth between items, when there could be a button for spawning secondary items.

Overall, I recommend this game.
